<h2>What Is Espresso?</h2>

<p>
  Espresso is produced by forcing <strong>hot water through finely-ground coffee at high pressure</strong>. The defining difference from drip brewing is pressure — approximately 9 bars (atmospheres) — which extracts 25–30ml of concentrated coffee in just 25–30 seconds.
</p>

<p>
  This high-pressure, short-duration process emulsifies <strong>coffee oils into the liquid as crema</strong>, creating the characteristic texture and mouthfeel unique to espresso. Espresso is consumed straight or used as the base for lattes, cappuccinos, americanos, and most café drinks.
</p>

<div class="info-box">
  <h4>Espresso Parameters (The Golden Ratio)</h4>
  <p>
    <strong>Input (dose):</strong> 18–20g (double shot)<br />
    <strong>Output (yield):</strong> 36–42g (~2× the input)<br />
    <strong>Extraction time:</strong> 25–32 seconds<br />
    <strong>Pressure:</strong> 9 bar (fixed)<br />
    <strong>Water temperature:</strong> 90–96°C (varies by roast level)<br />
    <strong>Grind:</strong> Extra fine (espresso-dedicated)
  </p>
</div>

<h2>What Is Crema?</h2>

<p>
  The cream-colored foam floating on espresso — <strong>crema</strong> — is an emulsion of coffee oils and CO₂ gas under high pressure, dispersed as a colloidal suspension. Crema indicates both correct extraction and bean freshness (CO₂ content correlates with time since roasting).
</p>

<p>
  More crema isn't always better. Beans roasted very recently release excess CO₂, which can actually disrupt even extraction. The general consensus: <strong>5–14 days post-roast</strong> is optimal for the best crema balance of oils and CO₂.
</p>

