<h2>Dialing In</h2>

<p>
  The process of optimizing an espresso shot is called <strong>dialing in</strong>. The three primary variables:
</p>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Variable</th><th>Adjustment Direction</th><th>Effect</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Grind size</strong></td><td>Finer</td><td>Slower extraction, more concentrated — over-extraction risk increases</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Grind size</strong></td><td>Coarser</td><td>Faster extraction, thinner — under-extraction risk increases</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Dose</strong></td><td>Increase</td><td>More resistance, slower extraction</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Temperature</strong></td><td>Higher</td><td>Better acid extraction — suits lighter roasts</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Tamping</strong></td><td>Even pressure</td><td>Prevents channeling, improves extraction uniformity</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>
  The goal: achieve your target output weight in <strong>25–32 seconds</strong>. If the shot runs too fast, grind finer. Too slow, grind coarser. This iterative adjustment is the core of dialing in.
</p>

<h2>Channeling and Even Extraction</h2>

<p>
  Espresso's primary quality enemy is <strong>channeling</strong>. When the coffee puck isn't packed evenly, high-pressure water finds the path of least resistance — flowing through one area (over-extracting it) while bypassing others (leaving them under-extracted). The result: a shot that tastes simultaneously sour and bitter.
</p>

<p>
  To prevent channeling: ① <strong>WDT (Weiss Distribution Technique)</strong> — use a thin needle or WDT tool to break up clumps and distribute grounds evenly before tamping; ② <strong>Level tamping</strong> — apply consistent, horizontal pressure with even force; ③ <strong>Quality grinder</strong> — a grinder with low fines and uniform particle distribution reduces channeling dramatically.
</p>

<div class="info-box">
  <h4>Espresso Flavor Diagnosis</h4>
  <p>
    <strong>Sour / thin (under-extracted)</strong> → Grind finer / raise temperature / extend time<br />
    <strong>Bitter / harsh (over-extracted)</strong> → Grind coarser / lower temperature / shorten time<br />
    <strong>Suspected channeling</strong> → Apply WDT / check tamping evenness<br />
    <strong>Thin crema</strong> → Check bean freshness / use beans 5–14 days post-roast
  </p>
</div>

<h2>Machine Anatomy</h2>

<p>
  From home machines to commercial workhorses, the core structure is consistent: a <strong>boiler</strong> heats and holds water at temperature; a <strong>pump</strong> generates 9-bar pressure; a <strong>group head</strong> (where the portafilter locks in) delivers pressurized water through the coffee puck.
</p>

<p>
  Higher-end machines add features like <strong>pre-infusion</strong> — a brief low-pressure soak of the puck before full pressure is applied, which helps water distribute evenly before extraction begins — and <strong>pressure profiling</strong>, which allows manual control of pressure curves throughout the shot for finer creative control.
</p>

